abstract: In the not-so-distant past, TV viewers were forced to wait a week for the next installment of their favorite shows, parceled out by networks in half-hour or hour-long increments.
snippet: In the not-so-distant past, TV viewers were forced to wait a week for the next installment of their favorite shows, parceled out by networks in half-hour or hour-long increments.
lead_paragraph: (Reuters) - In the not-so-distant past, TV viewers were forced to wait a week for the next installment of their favorite shows, parceled out by networks in half-hour or hour-long increments.
headline_main: The Netflix Decade: How One Company Changed the Way We Watch TV
headline_print_headline: The Netflix Decade: How One Company Changed the Way We Watch TV

abstract: Indian Muslims protesting against a citizenship law which they say is discriminatory are carrying national flags and copies of the constitution, aiming to prevent supporters of the Hindu nationalist government from painting them as anti-India.
snippet: Indian Muslims protesting against a citizenship law which they say is discriminatory are carrying national flags and copies of the constitution, aiming to prevent supporters of the Hindu nationalist government from painting them as anti-India.
lead_paragraph: NEW DELHI/BENGALURU — Indian Muslims protesting against a citizenship law which they say is discriminatory are carrying national flags and copies of the constitution, aiming to prevent supporters of the Hindu nationalist government from painting them as anti-India.
headline_main: Indian Muslims Wave National Flag to Show Protest Is Not Anti-India
headline_print_headline: Indian Muslims Wave National Flag to Show Protest Is Not Anti-India

abstract: Thailand's Constitutional Court says it will rule on a sedition complaint that claims a popular opposition political party is linked to the Illuminati, which conspiracy theorists say secretly seeks world domination.
snippet: Thailand's Constitutional Court says it will rule on a sedition complaint that claims a popular opposition political party is linked to the Illuminati, which conspiracy theorists say secretly seeks world domination.
lead_paragraph: BANGKOK — Thailand's Constitutional Court says it will rule on a sedition complaint that claims a popular opposition political party is linked to the Illuminati, which conspiracy theorists say secretly seeks world domination.
headline_main: Thai Court to Rule on Case Linking Opposition to Illuminati
headline_print_headline: Thai Court to Rule on Case Linking Opposition to Illuminati

abstract: Gen. Ahmed Gaïd Salah arranged the ouster of the country’s longtime president this year, while cracking down on a protest movement that demanded broader change.
snippet: Gen. Ahmed Gaïd Salah arranged the ouster of the country’s longtime president this year, while cracking down on a protest movement that demanded broader change.
lead_paragraph: PARIS — Algeria’s de facto ruler, Gen. Ahmed Gaïd Salah, who this year managed the ouster of one president and the ascent of another amid deep civil unrest, died on Monday, according to the state news agency and Algerian press reports.

abstract: Afghanistan's Electoral Complaints Commission said on Monday the election might go to a second round as it begins reviewing thousands of complaints a day after the preliminary result handed incumbent president Ashraf Ghani a narrow victory.
snippet: Afghanistan's Electoral Complaints Commission said on Monday the election might go to a second round as it begins reviewing thousands of complaints a day after the preliminary result handed incumbent president Ashraf Ghani a narrow victory.
lead_paragraph: KABUL — Afghanistan's Electoral Complaints Commission said on Monday the election might go to a second round as it begins reviewing thousands of complaints a day after the preliminary result handed incumbent president Ashraf Ghani a narrow victory.
headline_main: Afghan Election Runoff Likely Amid Thousands of Complaints: Officials
headline_print_headline: Afghan Election Runoff Likely Amid Thousands of Complaints: Officials

abstract: Donald Tusk is leaving his job as European Council president, but he still faces the problem presented by his old friend, transformed by power and cynicism.
snippet: Donald Tusk is leaving his job as European Council president, but he still faces the problem presented by his old friend, transformed by power and cynicism.
lead_paragraph: BRUSSELS — Donald Tusk grew up inside Poland’s Solidarity movement, the workers’ revolt that combined with intellectuals to bring down the Communist regime in the face of a Soviet threat of invasion and then martial law.

abstract: Iraqi politicians have missed another deadline to name a new prime minister because of disagreements over which is the largest bloc in parliament, deepening a crisis that has roiled the country since October amid mass protests and state crackdown that has killed hundreds of people.
snippet: Iraqi politicians have missed another deadline to name a new prime minister because of disagreements over which is the largest bloc in parliament, deepening a crisis that has roiled the country since October amid mass protests and state crackdown ...
lead_paragraph: BAGHDAD — Iraqi politicians have missed another deadline to name a new prime minister because of disagreements over which is the largest bloc in parliament, deepening a crisis that has roiled the country since October amid mass protests and state crackdown that has killed hundreds of people.
headline_main: Iraq Crisis Deepens as Politicians Miss Deadline to Name PM
headline_print_headline: Iraq Crisis Deepens as Politicians Miss Deadline to Name PM

abstract: Aiming an AR-15 rifle across a Colorado valley dotted with antelope and cattle, Drew Miller explains how members of his new survival ranch would ride out an apocalypse.

headline_main: Survival Camps Cater to New Fear: America's Political Unrest

abstract: The knowledge economy is today’s road to greater and more inclusive prosperity.
snippet: The knowledge economy is today’s road to greater and more inclusive prosperity.
lead_paragraph: CAMBRIDGE, Mass. — South America is falling apart. The popular rebellion in Chile — a country often held up as an example of success predicated on good behavior — is only the most extreme instance of a discontent that is either breaking out or simmering in almost every South American nation. The struggle between the right and the left has intensified. But so far nothing that contributes to socially inclusive economic growth has resulted from these protests. What does it all mean? And how do South America’s troubles mirror the United States’ own?

headline_main: How to Energize Democracy to Rebuild South America (and the U.S.)

abstract: Mitch McConnell and the other 99 senators must serve the institution and the Constitution that established it, not President Trump.
snippet: Mitch McConnell and the other 99 senators must serve the institution and the Constitution that established it, not President Trump.
lead_paragraph: When the Senate ultimately convenes to consider whether to remove the president from office, for just the third time in its history, it will convene not as a legislative body, but as a court of impeachment. And it will not just be President Trump on trial. The Senate — and indeed, truth itself — will stand trial.
